# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: falcon-api
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Guido van Rossum began working on Python in the late 1980s as a successor to the ABC programming language.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python 3.0, released in 2008, was a major revision and not completely backward-compatible with earlier versions.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Beginning with Python 3.5, capabilities and keywords for typing were added to the language, allowing optional static typing.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] As of 2026, the Python Software Foundation supports Python 3.10, 3.11, 3.12, 3.13, and 3.14, following the project's annual release cycle and five-year support policy.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python 3.15 is currently in the beta development phase, and the stable release is expected to launch in October 2026.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Earlier versions in the 3.x series have reached end-of-life and no longer receive security updates.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python has gained extensive use in the machine learning community.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] It is widely taught as an introductory programming language.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Since 2003, Python has consistently ranked among the top ten most popular programming languages in the TIOBE Programming Community Index, which ranks programming languages based on searches across 24 platforms.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python was conceived in the late 1980s by Guido van Rossum at Centrum Wiskunde & Informatica (CWI) in the Netherlands.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] It was designed as a successor to the ABC programming language, which was inspired by SETL, capable of exception handling and interfacing with the Amoeba operating system.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python implementation began in December 1989.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Van Rossum first released it in 1991 as Python 0.9.0.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] In January 2019, active Python core developers elected a five-member Steering Council to lead the project.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] The name *Python* derives from the British comedy series *Monty Python's Flying Circus*.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python 2.0 was released on 16 October 2000, featuring many new features such as list comprehensions, cycle-detecting garbage collection, reference counting, and Unicode support.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python 2.7's end-of-life was initially set for 2015, and then postponed to 2020 out of concern that a large body of existing code could not easily be forward-ported to Python 3.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] It no longer receives security patches or updates.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] While Python 2.7 and older versions are officially unsupported, a different unofficial Python implementation, PyPy, continues to support Python 2, i.e., "2.7.18+" (plus 3.11), with the plus signifying (at least some) "backported security updates".
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python 3.0 was released on 3 December 2008, and was a major revision and not completely backward-compatible with earlier versions, with some new semantics and changed syntax.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python 2.7.18, released in 2020, was the last release of Python 2.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Several releases in the Python 3.x series have added new syntax to the language, and made a few (considered very minor) backward-incompatible changes.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] As of May 2026, Python 3.14.6 is the latest stable release.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] All older 3.x versions had a security update down to Python 3.9.24 then again with 3.9.25, the final version in 3.9 series.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python 3.10 is, since November 2025, the oldest supported branch.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python 3.15 has an alpha released, and Android has an official downloadable executable available for Python 3.14.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Releases receive two years of full support followed by three years of security support.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python is a multi-paradigm programming language.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Object-oriented programming and structured programming are fully supported, and many of their features support functional programming and aspect-oriented programming – including metaprogramming and metaobjects.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Many other paradigms are supported via extensions, including design by contract and logic programming.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python is often referred to as a *'glue language'* because it is purposely designed to be able to integrate components written in other languages.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python uses dynamic typing and a combination of reference counting and a cycle-detecting garbage collector for memory management.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] It uses dynamic name resolution (late binding), which binds method and variable names during program execution.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python's design offers some support for functional programming in the "Lisp tradition".
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] It has `filter`, `map`, and `reduce` functions; list comprehensions, dictionaries, sets, and generator expressions.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] The standard library has two modules (`itertools` and `functools`) that implement functional tools borrowed from Haskell and Standard ML.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] However, Python has received criticism for violating these principles and adding unnecessary language bloat.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Responses to these criticisms note that the Zen of Python is a guideline rather than a rule.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] The addition of some new features had been controversial: Guido van Rossum resigned as *Benevolent Dictator for Life* after conflict about adding the assignment expression operator in Python 3.8.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Nevertheless, rather than building all functionality into its core, Python was designed to be highly extensible through modules.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] This compact modularity has made it particularly popular as a means of adding programmable interfaces to existing applications.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Van Rossum's vision of a small core language with a large standard library and an easily extensible interpreter stemmed from his frustrations with ABC, which represented the opposite approach.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python claims to strive for a simpler, less-cluttered syntax and grammar, while giving developers a choice in their coding methodology.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python lacks `do .. while` loops, which Rossum considered harmful.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] In contrast to Perl's motto "there is more than one way to do it", Python advocates an approach where "there should be one – and preferably only one – obvious way to do it".
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] In practice, however, Python provides many ways to achieve a given goal.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] There are at least three ways to format a string literal, with no certainty as to which one a programmer should use.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python's developers typically prioritize readability over performance.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] For example, they reject patches to non-critical parts of the CPython reference implementation that would offer increases in speed that do not justify the cost of clarity and readability.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Execution speed can be improved by moving speed-critical functions to extension modules written in languages such as C, or by using a just-in-time compiler like PyPy.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Also, it is possible to transpile to other languages.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] However, this approach either fails to achieve the expected speed-up, since Python is a very dynamic language, or only a restricted subset of Python is compiled (with potential minor semantic changes).
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python is meant to be a fun language to use.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] This goal is reflected in the name – a tribute to the British comedy group Monty Python – and in playful approaches to some tutorials and reference materials.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] For instance, some code examples use the terms "spam" and "eggs" (in reference to a Monty Python sketch), rather than the typical terms "foo" and "bar".
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] A common neologism in the Python community is *pythonic*, which has a broad range of meanings related to program style: Pythonic code may use Python idioms well; be natural or show fluency in the language; or conform with Python's minimalist philosophy and emphasis on readability.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] There are 3 kinds of PEPs, with those are being *standards track PEP*, *Informational PEP* and *Process PEP*s which has their own unique meanings.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] They were firstly introduced in 2000, inspired by other RfCs (requests for comments) and Desing Enhancement Proposals.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Most known PEPs are PEP – 1, PEP – 8, PEP – 20, PEP – 257 and others.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python is meant to be an easily readable language.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Its formatting is visually uncluttered and often uses English keywords where other languages use punctuation.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Unlike many other languages, it does not use curly brackets to delimit blocks, and semicolons after statements are allowed but rarely used.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] It has fewer syntactic exceptions and special cases than C or Pascal.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python uses whitespace indentation, rather than curly brackets or keywords, to delimit blocks.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] An increase in indentation comes after certain statements; a decrease in indentation signifies the end of the current block.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Thus, the program's visual structure accurately represents its semantic structure.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] This feature is sometimes termed the off-side rule.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Some other languages use indentation this way; but in most, indentation has no semantic meaning.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] The recommended indent size is four spaces.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] The assignment statement (`=`) binds a name as a reference to a separate, dynamically allocated object.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Variables may subsequently be rebound at any time to any object.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] In Python, a variable name is a generic reference holder without a fixed data type; however, it always refers to *some* object with a type.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] This is called dynamic typing—in contrast to statically-typed languages, where each variable may contain only a value of a certain type.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python does not support tail call optimization or first-class continuations; according to Van Rossum, the language never will.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] However, better support for coroutine-like functionality is provided by extending Python's generators.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Before 2.5, generators were lazy iterators; data was passed unidirectionally out of the generator.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] From Python 2.5 on, it is possible to pass data back into a generator function; and from version 3.3, data can be passed through multiple stack levels.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] In Python, a distinction between expressions and statements is rigidly enforced, in contrast to languages such as Common Lisp, Scheme, or Ruby.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] A statement cannot be part of an expression; because of this restriction, expressions such as list and `dict` comprehensions (and lambda expressions) cannot contain statements.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] As a particular case, an assignment statement such as `a = 1` cannot be part of the conditional expression of a conditional statement.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python uses duck typing, and it has typed objects but untyped variable names.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Type constraints are not checked at definition time; rather, operations on an object may fail at usage time, indicating that the object is not of an appropriate type.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Despite being dynamically typed, Python is strongly typed, forbidding operations that are poorly defined (e.g., adding a number and a string) rather than quietly attempting to interpret them.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python allows programmers to define their own types using classes, most often for object-oriented programming.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] New instances of classes are constructed by calling the class, for example, `SpamClass()` or `EggsClass()`); the classes are instances of the metaclass `type` (which is an instance of itself), thereby allowing metaprogramming and reflection.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Before version 3.0, Python had two kinds of classes, both using the same syntax: *old-style* and *new-style*.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Current Python versions support the semantics of only the new style.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python supports optional type annotations.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] These annotations are not enforced by the language, but may be used by external tools such as **mypy** to catch errors.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python includes a module `typing` including several type names for type annotations.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Also, mypy supports a Python compiler called mypyc, which leverages type annotations for optimization.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python includes conventional symbols for arithmetic operators (`+`, `-`, `*`, `/`), the floor-division operator `//`, and the modulo operator `%`.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] (With the modulo operator, a remainder can be negative, e.g., `4 % -3 == -2`.) Python also offers the `**` symbol for exponentiation, e.g.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] These operators work as in traditional mathematics; with the same precedence rules, the infix operators `+` and `-` can also be unary, to represent positive and negative numbers respectively.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Division between integers produces floating-point results.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] In Python terms, the `/` operator represents *true division* (or simply *division*), while the `//` operator represents *floor division.* Before version 3.0, the `/` operator represents *classic division*.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Rounding towards negative infinity, though a different method than in most languages, adds consistency to Python.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] For instance, this rounding implies that the equation `(a + b)//b == a//b + 1` is always true.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Also, the rounding implies that the equation `b*(a//b) + a%b == a` is valid for both positive and negative values of `a`.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] As expected, the result of `a%b` lies in the half-open interval [0, *b*), where `b` is a positive integer; however, maintaining the validity of the equation requires that the result must lie in the interval (*b*, 0] when `b` is negative.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python provides a `round` function for rounding a float to the nearest integer.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] For tie-breaking, Python 3 uses the *round to even* method: `round(1.5)` and `round(2.5)` both produce `2`.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python allows Boolean expressions that contain multiple equality relations to be consistent with general usage in mathematics.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] For example, the expression `a < b < c` tests whether `a` is less than `b` and `b` is less than `c`.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] C-derived languages interpret this expression differently: in C, the expression would first evaluate `a < b`, resulting in 0 or 1, and that result would then be compared with `c`.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python uses arbitrary-precision arithmetic for all integer operations.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] The `Decimal` type/class in the `decimal` module provides decimal floating-point numbers to a pre-defined arbitrary precision with several rounding modes.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] The `Fraction` class in the `fractions` module provides arbitrary precision for rational numbers.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Due to Python's extensive mathematics library and the third-party library NumPy, the language is frequently used for scientific scripting in tasks such as numerical data processing and manipulation.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Functions are created in Python by using the `def` keyword.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] A function is defined similarly to how it is called, by first providing the function name and then the required parameters.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] To assign a default value to a function parameter in case no actual value is provided at run time, variable-definition syntax can be used inside the function header.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python's large standard library is commonly cited as one of its greatest strengths.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] For Internet-facing applications, many standard formats and protocols such as MIME and HTTP are supported.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] The language includes modules for creating graphical user interfaces, connecting to relational databases, generating pseudorandom numbers, arithmetic with arbitrary-precision decimals, manipulating regular expressions, and unit testing.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Some parts of the standard library are covered by specifications—for example, the Web Server Gateway Interface (WSGI) implementation `wsgiref` follows PEP 333—but most parts are specified by their code, internal documentation, and test suites.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] However, because most of the standard library is cross-platform Python code, only a few modules must be altered or rewritten for variant implementations.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] As of 13 March 2025, the Python Package Index (PyPI), the official repository for third-party Python software, contains over 614,339 packages.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Most Python implementations (including CPython) include a read–eval–print loop (REPL); this permits the environment to function as a command line interpreter, with which users enter statements sequentially and receive results immediately.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Also, CPython is bundled with an integrated development environment (IDE) called IDLE, which is oriented toward beginners.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Other shells, including IDLE and IPython, add additional capabilities such as improved auto-completion, session-state retention, and syntax highlighting.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] CPython is the reference implementation of Python.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] This implementation is written in C, meeting the C11 standard since version 3.11.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Older versions use the C89 standard with several select C99 features, but third-party extensions are not limited to older C versions—e.g., they can be implemented using C11 or C++.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] CPython compiles Python programs into an intermediate bytecode, which is then executed by a virtual machine.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] CPython is distributed with a large standard library written in a combination of C and native Python.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] CPython is available for many platforms, including Windows and most modern Unix-like systems, including macOS (and Apple M1 Macs, since Python 3.9.1, using an experimental installer).
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Starting with Python 3.9, the Python installer intentionally fails to install on Windows 7 and 8; Windows XP was supported until Python 3.5.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Old Python versions unofficially support VMS (mostly supporting) and OpenVMS x86-64 has Python 3.10 support.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Platform portability was one of Python's earliest priorities.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] During development of Python 1 and 2, even OS/2 and Solaris were supported; since that time, support has been dropped for many platforms.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] All current Python versions (since 3.7) support only operating systems that feature multithreading, by now supporting not nearly as many operating systems (dropping many outdated) than in the past.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] All alternative implementations have at least slightly different semantics.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] For example, an alternative may include unordered dictionaries, in contrast to other current Python versions.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] As another example in the larger Python ecosystem, PyPy does not support the full C Python API.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Creating an executable with Python often is done by bundling an entire Python interpreter into the executable, which causes binary sizes to be massive for small programs, yet there exist implementations that are capable of truly compiling Python.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Stackless Python is a significant fork of CPython that implements microthreads.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] This implementation uses the call stack differently, thus allowing massively concurrent programs.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] A performance comparison among various Python implementations, using a non-numerical (combinatorial) workload, was presented at EuroSciPy '13.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] In addition, Python's performance relative to other programming languages is benchmarked by The Computer Language Benchmarks Game.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] There are several approaches to optimizing Python performance, despite the inherent slowness of an interpreted language.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python's development is conducted mostly through the *Python Enhancement Proposal* (PEP) process; this process is the primary mechanism for proposing major new features, collecting community input on issues, and documenting Python design decisions.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python coding style is covered in PEP 8.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Outstanding PEPs are reviewed and commented on by the Python community and the steering council.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Enhancement of the language corresponds with development of the CPython reference implementation.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] The mailing list python-dev is the primary forum for the language's development.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Specific issues were originally discussed in the Roundup bug tracker hosted by the foundation.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] In 2022, all issues and discussions were migrated to GitHub.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Development originally took place on a self-hosted source-code repository running Mercurial, until Python moved to GitHub in January 2017.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Many alpha, beta, and release-candidates are also released as previews and for testing before final releases.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Although there is a rough schedule for releases, they are often delayed if the code is not ready yet.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python's development team monitors the state of the code by running a large unit test suite during development.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] The major academic conference on Python is PyCon.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Also, there are special Python mentoring programs, such as PyLadies.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python's name is inspired by the British comedy group Monty Python, whom Python creator Guido van Rossum enjoyed while developing the language.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Monty Python references appear frequently in Python code and culture; for example, the metasyntactic variables often used in Python literature are *spam* and *eggs*, rather than the traditional *foo* and *bar*.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Also, the official Python documentation contains various references to Monty Python routines.
[src:falcon-api/python-programming-language] Python users are sometimes referred to as "Pythonistas".
