[src:falcon-api/representational-state-transfer] REST has been employed throughout the software industry to create stateless, reliable, web-based applications.
[src:falcon-api/representational-state-transfer] The term *representational state transfer* was introduced and defined in 2000 by computer scientist Roy Fielding in his doctoral dissertation.
[src:falcon-api/representational-state-transfer] It means that a server will respond with the representation of a resource (today, it will most often be an HTML document) and that resource will contain hypermedia links that can be followed to make the state of the system change.
[src:falcon-api/representational-state-transfer] Any such request will in turn receive the representation of a resource, and so on.
[src:falcon-api/representational-state-transfer] An important consequence is that the only identifier that needs to be known is the identifier of the first resource requested, and all other identifiers will be discovered.
[src:falcon-api/representational-state-transfer] This means that those identifiers can change without the need to inform the client beforehand and that client and server must be inherently loosely coupled.
[src:falcon-api/representational-state-transfer] The Web began to enter everyday use in 1993–1994, when websites for general use started to become available.
[src:falcon-api/representational-state-transfer] At the time, only a fragmented description existed of the Web's architecture, and there was pressure within the community to agree on a standard for the Web interface protocols.
[src:falcon-api/representational-state-transfer] For instance, several experimental extensions had been added to the communication protocol (HTTP) to support proxies, and more extensions were being proposed, but there was a need for a formal Web architecture with which to evaluate the impact of these changes.
[src:falcon-api/representational-state-transfer] The W3C and IETF working groups together started work on creating formal descriptions of the Web's three primary standards: URI, HTTP, and HTML.
[src:falcon-api/representational-state-transfer] Fielding defined REST in his 2000 PhD dissertation "Architectural Styles and the Design of Network-based Software Architectures" at UC Irvine.
[src:falcon-api/representational-state-transfer] To create the REST architectural style, Fielding identified the requirements that apply when creating a world-wide network-based application, such as the need for a low entry barrier to enable global adoption.
[src:falcon-api/representational-state-transfer] He also surveyed many existing architectural styles for network-based applications, identifying which features are shared with other styles, such as caching and client–server features, and those which are unique to REST, such as the concept of resources.
[src:falcon-api/representational-state-transfer] Fielding was trying to both categorise the existing architecture of the current implementation and identify which aspects should be considered central to the behavioural and performance requirements of the Web.
[src:falcon-api/representational-state-transfer] By their nature, architectural styles are independent of any specific implementation, and while REST was created as part of the development of the Web standards, the implementation of the Web does not obey every constraint in the REST architectural style.
[src:falcon-api/representational-state-transfer] Mismatches can occur due to ignorance or oversight, but the existence of the REST architectural style means that they can be identified before they become standardised.
[src:falcon-api/representational-state-transfer] For example, Fielding identified the embedding of session information in URIs as a violation of the constraints of REST which can negatively affect shared caching and server scalability.
[src:falcon-api/representational-state-transfer] HTTP cookies also violate REST constraints because they can become out of sync with the browser's application state, making them unreliable; they also contain opaque data that can be a concern for privacy and security.
[src:falcon-api/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style is designed for network-based applications, specifically client-server applications.
[src:falcon-api/representational-state-transfer] But more than that, it is designed for Internet-scale usage, so the coupling between the *user agent* (client) and the *origin server* must be as loose as possible to facilitate large-scale adoption.
[src:falcon-api/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style defines six guiding constraints.
[src:falcon-api/representational-state-transfer] When these constraints are applied to the system architecture, it gains desirable non-functional properties, such as performance, scalability, simplicity, modifiability, visibility, portability, and reliability.
[src:falcon-api/representational-state-transfer] The uniform interface constraint is fundamental to the design of any RESTful system.
[src:falcon-api/representational-state-transfer] It simplifies and decouples the architecture, which enables each part to evolve independently.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] A **web API** is an application programming interface (API) for either a web server or a web browser.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] As a web development concept, it can be related to a web application's client side (including any web frameworks being used).
[src:falcon-api/web-api] A server-side web API consists of one or more publicly exposed **endpoints** to a defined request–response message system, typically expressed in JSON or XML by means of an HTTP-based web server.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] A server API (SAPI) is not considered a server-side web API, unless it is publicly accessible by a remote web application.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] A client-side web API is a programmatic interface to extend functionality within a web browser or other HTTP client.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] Originally these were most commonly in the form of native plug-in browser extensions however most newer ones target standardized JavaScript bindings.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] The Mozilla Foundation created their WebAPI specification which is designed to help replace native mobile applications with HTML5 applications.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] Google created their Native Client architecture which is designed to help replace insecure native plug-ins with secure native sandboxed extensions and applications.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] They have also made this portable by employing a modified LLVM AOT compiler.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] A server-side web API consists of one or more publicly exposed *endpoints* to a defined request–response message system, typically expressed in JSON or XML.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] The web API is exposed most commonly by means of an HTTP-based web server.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] Endpoints are important aspects of interacting with server-side web APIs, as they specify where resources can be accessed by third-party software.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] Usually the access is via a URI to which HTTP requests are posted, and from which the response is thus expected.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] Web APIs may be public or private, the latter of which requires an *access token*.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] Endpoints need to be static, otherwise the correct functioning of software that interacts with them cannot be guaranteed.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] If the location of a resource changes (and with it the endpoint) then previously written software will break, as the required resource can no longer be found at the same place.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] As API providers still want to update their web APIs, many have introduced a versioning system in the URI that points to an endpoint.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] Web 2.0 Web APIs often use machine-based interactions such as REST and SOAP.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] RESTful web APIs use HTTP methods to access resources via URL-encoded parameters, and use JSON or XML to transmit data.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] By contrast, SOAP protocols are standardized by the W3C and mandate the use of XML as the payload format, typically over HTTP.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] Furthermore, SOAP-based Web APIs use XML validation to ensure structural message integrity, by leveraging the XML schemas provisioned with WSDL documents.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] A WSDL document accurately defines the XML messages and transport bindings of a Web service.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] Server-side web APIs are interfaces for the outside world to interact with the business logic.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] For many companies this internal business logic and the intellectual property associated with it are what distinguishes them from other companies, and potentially what gives them a competitive edge.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] They do not want this information to be exposed.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] However, in order to provide a web API of high quality, there *needs* to be a sufficient level of documentation.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] One API provider that not only provides documentation, but also links to it in its error messages is Twilio.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] However, there are now directories of popular documented server-side web APIs.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] The number of available web APIs has grown consistently over the past years, as businesses realize the growth opportunities associated with running an open platform, that any developer can interact with.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] ProgrammableWeb tracks over 24000 Web APIs that were available in 2022, up from 105 in 2005.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] There are few major software applications/services that do not offer some form of web API.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] One of the most common forms of interacting with these web APIs is via embedding external resources, such as tweets, Facebook comments, YouTube videos, etc.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] In fact there are very successful companies, such as Disqus, whose main service is to provide embeddable tools, such as a feature-rich comment system.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] Any website of the TOP 100 Alexa Internet ranked websites uses APIs and/or provides its own APIs, which is a very distinct indicator for the prodigious scale and impact of web APIs as a whole.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] As the number of available web APIs has grown, open source tools have been developed to provide more sophisticated search and discovery.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] APIs.json provides a machine-readable description of an API and its operations, and the related project APIs.io offers a searchable public listing of APIs based on the APIs.json metadata format.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] Many companies and organizations rely heavily on their Web API infrastructure to serve their core business clients.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] In 2014 Netflix received around 5 billion API requests, most of them within their private API.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] Many governments collect a lot of data, and some governments are now opening up access to this data.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] The interfaces through which this data is typically made accessible are web APIs.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] Web APIs allow for data, such as "budget, public works, crime, legal, and other agency data" to be accessed by any developer in a convenient manner.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] An example of a popular web API is the Astronomy Picture of the Day API operated by the American space agency NASA.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] It is a server-side API used to retrieve photographs of space or other images of interest to astronomers, and metadata about the images.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] The documentation states that this endpoint accepts GET requests.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] It requires one piece of information from the user, an API key, and accepts several other optional pieces of information.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] Such pieces of information are known as *parameters*.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] The parameters for this API are written in a format known as a query string, which is separated by a question mark character (`?`) from the endpoint.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] An ampersand (`&`) separates the parameters in the query string from each other.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] Together, the endpoint and the query string form a URL that determines how the API will respond.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] This URL is also known as a *query* or an *API call*.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] In the below example, two parameters are transmitted (or *passed*) to the API via the query string.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] The first is the required API key and the second is an optional parameter — the date of the photograph requested.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] Visiting the above URL in a web browser will initiate a GET request, calling the API and showing the user a result, known as a *return value* or as a *return*.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] This API returns JSON, a type of data format intended to be understood by computers, but which is somewhat easy for a human to read as well.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] The above API return has been reformatted so that names of JSON data items, known as *keys*, appear at the start of each line.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] Although this API can be called by an end user with a web browser (as in this example) it is intended to be called automatically by software or by computer programmers while writing software.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] JSON is intended to be parsed by a computer program, which would extract the URL of the photograph and the other metadata.
[src:falcon-api/web-api] The resulting photo could be embedded in a website, automatically sent via text message, or used for any other purpose envisioned by a software developer.
[src:falcon-api/web-server-gateway-interface] The **Web Server Gateway Interface** (**WSGI**, pronounced *whiskey* or *WIZ-ghee*) is a simple calling convention for web servers to forward requests to web applications or frameworks written in the Python programming language.
[src:falcon-api/web-server-gateway-interface] The current version of WSGI, version 1.0.1, is specified in Python Enhancement Proposal (PEP) 3333.
[src:falcon-api/web-server-gateway-interface] WSGI was originally specified as PEP-333 in 2003.
[src:falcon-api/web-server-gateway-interface] PEP-3333, published in 2010, updates the specification for Python 3.
[src:falcon-api/web-server-gateway-interface] In 2003, Python web frameworks were typically written against only CGI, FastCGI, mod_python, or some other custom API of a specific web server.
[src:falcon-api/web-server-gateway-interface] WSGI was thus created as an implementation-neutral interface between web servers and web applications or frameworks to promote common ground for portable web application development.
[src:falcon-api/web-server-gateway-interface] Between the server and the application, there may be one or more *WSGI middleware components*, which implement both sides of the API, typically in Python code.
[src:falcon-api/web-server-gateway-interface] WSGI does not specify how the Python interpreter should be started, nor how the application object should be loaded or configured, and different frameworks and webservers achieve this in different ways.
[src:falcon-api/web-server-gateway-interface] A WSGI middleware component is a Python callable that is itself a WSGI application, but may handle requests by delegating to other WSGI applications.
[src:falcon-api/web-server-gateway-interface] These applications can themselves be WSGI middleware components.
[src:falcon-api/web-server-gateway-interface] A full example of a WSGI network server is outside the scope of this article.
[src:falcon-api/web-server-gateway-interface] Below is a sketch of how one would call a WSGI application and retrieve its HTTP status line, response headers, and response body, as Python objects.
[src:falcon-api/web-server-gateway-interface] Details of how to construct the `environ` dict have been omitted.
[src:falcon-api/web-server-gateway-interface] Currently wrappers are available for FastCGI, CGI, SCGI, AJP (using flup), twisted.web, Apache (using mod_wsgi or mod_python), Nginx (using ngx_http_uwsgi_module), Nginx Unit (using the Python language module), and Microsoft IIS (using WFastCGI, isapi-wsgi, PyISAPIe, or an ASP gateway).
